"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89429","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-09","<p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Growth Deals were bespoke to each LEP area and negotiated with Government based on each LEP’s multi-year Strategic Economic Plan, taking into account their priorities for which interventions would drive economic growth in their area. Greater Cambridge Greater Peterborough LEP submitted two proposals to support existing business support initiatives. GCGP LEP prioritised one of the proposals, the Agri-tech fund, during negotiations, which received £1.55m in 2015/16 in their Growth Deal.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-09-09T14:43:59.0623316Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89429/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89429/answer","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89429/answer/previousversion/17976","Biography information for Greg Clark","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Local Enterprise Partnerships: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, for what reasons the new Anglia LEP has received an extension on its loan facility but the Greater Cambridge Greater Peterborough LEP was refused a similar request.","false","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","207492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89430","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-10","<p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We have identified one licence for components for unmanned air vehicles for the Israeli Defence Forces, dating back to 1999.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-10T14:23:26.3543752Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89430/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89430/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Unmanned Air Vehicles: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether the engines used in the Israeli Defence Forces unmanned aerial vehicles have been developed or enhanced with the assistance of UK technology or components.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","207381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89431","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-08","<p>When asked to support an export transaction, UK Export Finance conducts due diligence on the companies involved in that transaction. It does not research other unrelated companies, for example using the same registered address of convenience, which have no connection with the transaction in question.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-08T13:57:37.7236236Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89431/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89431/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Jackson Square Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when conducting due diligence on Jackson Square Aviation and JSA International Holdings LP, whether UK Export Finance was aware that their base at Walker House is also the base of Iranian banks on the UK's blacklists.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","207296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89432","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-10","<p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK’s priority in arms export licensing is to ensure that all applications are rigorously assessed on a case-by-case basis against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria prior to granting a licence. This includes assessing the risk of diversion to undesirable end use or undesirable end users.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>After the export has been granted, the Export Control Organisation also has the power to suspend and revoke licences if necessary, if the situation in the end-use destination changes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In terms of end use monitoring, Foreign Office posts overseas have a standing requirement to monitor developments in human rights and conflicts in their respective countries or regions and to report back if there are any developments that might affect licensing policy. In addition the Government uses open source material such as NGO reports to make it assessments.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-10T14:14:46.7044183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89432/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89432/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Arms Trade: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what end-of-use monitoring is in place to ensure that UK weapons supplied to Saudi Arabia are used for the purposes specified.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","207361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89433","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-08","<p>The Government has not made a specific assessment of the competitiveness of the prosthesis manufacturing industry. However, prosthetics form a key part of the wider medical technology sector, and work is underway with the main medical technology trade associations (including the British Healthcare Trades Association (BHTA)), under the aegis of the Ministerial Medical Technology Strategy Group to identify and address the competitiveness challenges across the sector and its supply-chains.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-08T16:20:12.4759148Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89433/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89433/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Prosthetics: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the competitiveness of the prosthesis manufacturing industry.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","207338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89434","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-10","<p>No licences have been granted for unmanned aerial vehicle engines for use by the Israeli Defence Force since 2010.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-10-10T12:43:46.8260612Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89434/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89434/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Unmanned Air Vehicles: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether the Government has issued export licences for unmanned aerial vehicle engines for use by the Israeli Defence Force since 2010.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","207373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89435","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-08","<p>Through the Tradeshow Access Programme (TAP) 7 grants of £1,500 each are being made available for eligible UK businesses at the World Nuclear Exhibition.</p><p>A company can be eligible if they:</p><p>- are classed as small or medium-sized or a UK university or UK publicly funded centre of higher or further learning or UK publicly funded research organisation;</p><p>- have been exporting for less than 10 years or did not exhibit at the previous edition of the event in question; and</p><p>- do not breach a limit of 12 TAP grants since 1 April 2009 including no more than 6 in non-emerging and high growth markets.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-08T16:38:27.2959911Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89435/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89435/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Nuclear Power: Tradeshow Access Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what financial support is available from UK Trade & Investment to British companies under the Tradeshow Access Programme to attend the World Nuclear Exhibition in Paris from 14-16 October 2014; and what criteria are applied in deciding what support to provide.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","207374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89436","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-08","<p>The Overseas Business Risk (OBR) service is promoted as part of UK Trade and Investment’s (UKTI) overall offer to UK businesses looking to develop their exports. This is done through UKTI’s network which includes International Trade Advisers, Sectoral and Overseas teams. Promotion material, such as UKTI’s First Class Export Pack, also aims to ensure UK business is aware of the service alongside outreach events and the use of social media. The OBR country pages on the GOV.UK domain are refreshed on a regular basis to provide up-to-date intelligence to UK business. A Joint Advisory Group, with very senior business representation, contributes to the development and promotion of this service.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-08T16:41:12.2802532Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89436/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89436/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Exports: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that the Overseas Business Risk service is better shared with and promoted to businesses looking to export.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bingham","High Peak","Andrew Bingham","207306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89438","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-05","<p>The Government is committed to increasing compliance with minimum wage legislation and effective enforcement of it. Everyone who is entitled to the minimum wage should receive it.</p><p>All 30 employers that have been named and shamed up to 8 June 2014 were issued with a Notice of Underpayment (NoU) and were still in existence when the NoU was issued.</p><p>The Department’s answer to the Hon. Member’s parliamentary question of 25 June 2014 (Official Report, column 246W) sets out the months that the NoU were issued. HMRC do not record the time between the date of each underpayment and the issue of the Notice of Underpayment. HMRC can pursue arrears claims for workers going back up to six years and therefore a worker may complain up to six years after the time they think they were underpaid. Additionally, investigations following a complaint may identify further underpaid workers or other periods of underpayment going back several years.</p><p>All of the employers who were named and shamed paid the arrears due to workers and also the financial penalty imposed.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-09-05T13:43:47.8404763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89438/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89438/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 25 June 2014, Official Report, column 246W, on the national minimum wage, how many of the firms named and shamed for breach of the national minimum wage up to 8 June 2014 were issued notices of underpayments once the firm had dissolved; what the time was between each underpayment and the time of issuing of notice; how many of the employers named and shamed (a) paid their employees the underpayment and (b) paid a financial penalty to the Government; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","207292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89439","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-11","<p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>10 decisions for Standard Individual Export Licences were made for direct export to Israel.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A further 4 decisions for Standard Individual Export Licences were made for export, where Israel is listed as either an ultimate end user or potential ultimate end user on the application.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In total 14 decisions were made and all were for licences to be granted.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-11T15:38:53.0900797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89439/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89439/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Exports: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many decisions on standard individual export licence applications for export to Israel were made between 8 July and 31 July 2014; and what proportion of such decisions were approved.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","207349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89440","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-10","<p>19 applications have been submitted for Standard Individual Export Licences for direct export to Israel.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A further 16 applications have been submitted for Standard Individual Export Licences for export, where Israel is listed an ultimate end user on the application.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Of the 35 applications, 2 licences have been granted.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Our assessment is that the licences granted are not for items that could be used by Israeli forces in operations in Gaza in response to attacks in Hamas.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-10-10T12:32:09.3918129Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89440/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89440/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Exports: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many applications for standard individual export licences for export to Israel were made between 8 July 2014 and 31 July 2014; and how many such applications were successful.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","207350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89441","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-08","<p>The UK Government is a strong supporter of the Trade in Services Agreement (TiSA), which provides an opportunity to address barriers to trade in services through seeking to deepen services trade rules and regulatory disciplines and to address market access objectives. Given the crucial role of financial stability to overall economic stability, governments and regulators need to have the ability to closely monitor and regulate banks, insurance companies and other financial services providers. The TiSA text will contain a prudential carve-out which will fully protect the ability of UK and international financial regulators to regulate and take any prudential actions for the sake of financial stability or to protect investors, depositors, policy holders or persons to whom a fiduciary duty is owed by a financial service supplier.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-08T16:35:53.6786501Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89441/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89441/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Trade in Services Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of UK participation in a Trade in Services Agreement treaty on the Government's ability to regulate the financial services sector.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","207180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89442","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-10","<p> </p><p>No such export licences were suspended in this period of time.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-10T15:01:55.2280215Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89442/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89442/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Exports: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many (a) standard individual export licenses and (b) open individual export licences permitting exports to Israel were suspended between 8 July and 31 August 2014.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","207395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89443","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-10","<p>8 decisions for Standard Individual Export Licences were made for direct export to Israel, all of which were decisions to grant a licence.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Our assessment is that the licences granted are not for items that could be used by Israeli forces in operations in Gaza in response to attacks in Hamas.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-10-10T12:39:18.2985101Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89443/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89443/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Exports: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many decisions on standard individual export licence applications for export to Israel were made between 1 and 31 August 2014; and what proportion of the decisions on such applications were successful.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","207393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89444","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-08","<p>As with other trade agreements currently in place, such as the WTO General Agreement on Trade in Services, we expect agreements under negotiation, such as the Trade in Services Agreement, to contain provisions regarding data transfer and provisions regarding data protection. As with other agreements, we will want to see these provisions provide robust safeguards for the protection of EU citizens’ data while at the same time allowing for legitimate data transfers to third countries.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-08T16:30:06.1971359Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89444/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89444/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Trade in Services Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what information his Department holds on whether the proposed Trade in Services Agreement treaty is likely to contain provisions that would deny governments the right to require that data is held onshore.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","207178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89445","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-08","<p>The UK Government is a strong supporter of the Trade in Services Agreement (TiSA), which provides an opportunity to address barriers to trade in services through seeking to deepen services trade rules and regulatory disciplines and to address market access objectives. There is no intention to prevent the regulation of new insurance products, nor would the UK endorse such a move. Furthermore, the prudential carve-out element of the TiSA agreement will fully protect the ability of UK and international financial regulators to regulate and take any prudential actions for the sake of financial stability or to protect investors, depositors, policy holders or persons to whom a fiduciary duty is owed by a financial service supplier.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-08T16:33:04.1232169Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89445/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89445/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Trade in Services Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what information his Department holds on whether the proposed Trade in Services Agreement treaty is likely to contain provisions to prevent the regulation of new insurance products.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","207179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89446","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-10","<p>30 applications have been submitted for Standard Individual Export Licences for direct export to Israel.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A further 7 applications have been submitted for Standard Individual Export Licences for export, where Israel is listed as a potential or ultimate end user on the application.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Of the 37 applications, 2 licences have been granted.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Our assessment is that the licences granted are not for items that could be used by Israeli forces in operations in Gaza in response to attacks in Hamas.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-10-10T12:41:30.4549541Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89446/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89446/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Exports: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many applications for standard individual export licences for export to Israel were made between 1 and 31 August 2014; and how many such applications were successful.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","207394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89447","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-04","<p>During 2013 four televisions were purchased by the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) at a total cost of £2,363.83.</p><p>2014 to date, BIS has not purchased any televisions.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-09-04T14:56:20.1947152Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89447/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89447/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Television","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much his Department spent on the purchase of televisions in (a) 2013 and (b) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","207207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89448","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-08","<p>The European Commission has made it clear that safeguards are in place in all EU wide trade agreements to ensure that Member State governments remain free to manage public services as they wish.</p><p><a href="http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/press/index.cfm?id=1115" target="_blank">http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/press/index.cfm?id=1115</a></p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-08T16:47:58.0907337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89448/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89448/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Trade in Services Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what information his Department holds on whether the proposed Trade in Services Agreement treaty is likely to contain provisions to allow or promote the increased privatisation of public services.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","207176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89449","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-09","<p>The UK Government is a strong supporter of the Trade in Services Agreement, which provides an opportunity to address barriers to trade in services through seeking to deepen services trade rules and regulatory disciplines and to address market access objectives. Given the crucial role of financial stability to overall economic stability, governments and regulators need to have the ability to closely monitor and regulate banks, insurance companies and other financial services providers. The TiSA text will contain a prudential carve-out which will fully protect the ability of UK and international financial regulators to regulate and take any prudential actions for the sake of financial stability or to protect investors, depositors, policy holders or persons to whom a fiduciary duty is owed by a financial service supplier.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-09T15:34:45.6289375Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89449/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89449/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Trade in Services Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what information his Department holds on whether the proposed Trade in Services Agreement treaty is likely to contain provisions to prevent increased regulation of the financial services sector.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","207177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89450","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-08","<p>My Rt. Hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills has had no recent discussions directly concerning the removal of the CXL sugar import duty, or on improving access to the EU sugar market for cane sugar suppliers. The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills is involved in ongoing trade negotiations between the EU and various trading partners which aim to increase trade of goods, and this includes sugar cane imports.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-08T16:45:22.0007429Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89450/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89450/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Sugar: EU External Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent discussions he has had on (a) improving access to the EU sugar market for cane sugar suppliers and (b) removal of the CXL sugar import duty.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","207077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89451","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-05","<p>The Government’s response to the consultation held in 2012/13 will be published soon and once it is, BIS officials will be very happy to meet with pedlar stakeholders.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-09-05T13:46:30.914778Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89451/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89451/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Street Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, on what date his Department plans to meet pedlar stakeholders to discuss Consultation documents BIS/12/605 and 606 on street trading and pedlar laws as proposed by his Department via email on 19 December 2013.","false","Biography information for Dan Byles","North Warwickshire","Dan Byles","207078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89452","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-05","<p>Details of all EU legislation, including full details of all EU directives that have come into force since May 2010, can be found on the European Commission's website:</p><p><a href="http://eur-lex.europa.eu/homepage.html" target="_blank">http://eur-lex.europa.eu/homepage.html</a></p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-09-05T13:36:22.8373371Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89452/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89452/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many new EU directives and regulations have been transposed into UK law by his Department since May 2010.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","Mr John Redwood","207251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89453","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-08","<p>The UK Government recognises the importance of trade to delivering long term growth and jobs. The Trade in Services Agreement (TiSA) is the first negotiation to focus solely on trade in services, an area of key UK competitive advantage. As the second largest exporter of services, with 6.5% of global trade, the UK is a strong supporter of the TiSA. Independent analysis shows that an ambitious agreement could add as much as £2-3 billion annually to the UK economy in the long-term.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-08T16:43:19.3752775Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89453/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89453/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Trade in Services Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, for what reasons the UK decided to take part in the negotiations relating to the Trade in Services Agreement.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","207174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89454","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-08","<p>Information on the Trade in Services Agreement (TiSA) can be found on the European Commission’s dedicated TISA website - <a href="http://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/in-focus/tisa/" target="_blank">http://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/in-focus/tisa/</a> . In a bid to encourage transparency, the EU has published its initial TiSA offer from November 2013, the EU proposal for core text provisions based on the World Trade Organisation’s General Agreement on Trade in Services (GATS) and the EU proposal on financial services.</p><p>Whilst the Commission are committed to publishing as much information as possible on the TiSA, for trade negotiations to work and succeed, it is necessary that there is a degree of confidentiality surrounding the negotiating texts to ensure that the best deals are obtained.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-09-08T16:25:48.0958549Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89454/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89454/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-08-29","Trade in Services Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, for what reasons the text of the proposed Trade in Services Agreement treaty has not been made public.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","207175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89455","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-05","<p>The Cabinet Office has not had any discussions with NESTA regarding funding for the Big Society Network, and did not approach NESTA or Big Lottery Fund and ask them to fund the Big Society Network.</p><p>No discussions with Big Lottery Fund concerning the Society Network Foundation or Big Society Network were held by either Cabinet Office Ministers or Officials.</p><p>Cabinet Office holds regular sponsorship meetings with Big Lottery Fund, which cover governance, accounting and efficiency issues but not funding applications or decisions.</p><p> </p>","Braintree","Mr Brooks Newmark","207303 ; 207321","2014-09-05T11:16:21.4067223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89455/answer","Biography information for Mr Brooks Newmark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89455/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","Big Society Network","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether his Department has approached (a) NESTA and (b) Big Lottery to request them to fund the Big Society Network or the Social Network Foundation.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","207320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89456","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-05","<p>The Cabinet Office has not had any discussions with NESTA regarding funding for the Big Society Network, and did not approach NESTA or Big Lottery Fund and ask them to fund the Big Society Network.</p><p>No discussions with Big Lottery Fund concerning the Society Network Foundation or Big Society Network were held by either Cabinet Office Ministers or Officials.</p><p>Cabinet Office holds regular sponsorship meetings with Big Lottery Fund, which cover governance, accounting and efficiency issues but not funding applications or decisions.</p><p> </p>","Braintree","Mr Brooks Newmark","207303 ; 207320","2014-09-05T11:16:21.5476605Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89456/answer","Biography information for Mr Brooks Newmark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89456/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","Big Society Network","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent discussions his Department has had with NESTA on funding the Big Society Network.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","207321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89457","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-05","<p>The Get In project experienced difficulties in its first quarter. The Cabinet Office worked with Society Network Foundation to assess whether these difficulties could be overcome. When it was concluded that they could not, the project was stopped and Cabinet Office paid only up to that point. This is standard practice when funding small charities to undertake innovative projects.</p><p>The Civil Society Compact states that funders should attempt to support organisations overcome difficulties and should give at least three months’ notice before ending a financial relationship with a charitable organisation.</p><p>The Social Investment Business is currently following their standard procedure to investigate and take appropriate action where funds received by Social Network Foundation for the Get In project may not have been used for the purposes for which the grant was given.</p><p>Regarding grant funds spent on the Get In project, Cabinet Office would not normally seek to recover funds spent in line with a grant agreement.</p><p> </p>","Braintree","Mr Brooks Newmark","207325","2014-09-05T11:11:36.9538379Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89457/answer","Biography information for Mr Brooks Newmark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89457/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","Big Society Network","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he is taking to recover the money spent on the Get In project.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","207322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89458","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-05","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office and the Deputy Prime Minister’s Office are an integral part of the Cabinet Office.</p><p>refer the hon. Member to the answer given by my Rt Hon Friend the member for Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner to the hon. Member for Barnsley East on 8 October 2013, (Official Report) Column Ref: 170W.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-09-05T10:59:10.0703863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89458/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89458/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89458/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","Television","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much (a) his Department, (b) the Prime Minister's Office and (c) the Deputy Prime Minister's Office spent on televisions in (i) 2013 and (ii) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","207131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89459","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-03","<p>As with all outsourcing arrangements, security and information assurance measures are being implemented in line with the Government’s Information Assurance Standards, Good Practice Guides, Government Security Policy Framework and Data Protection Act. These Government security requirements were introduced under the previous Government and applied to outsourcing then. All shared services data will be handled, processed and transmitted in accordance with these security requirements, taking into consideration clients’ security policies.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-09-03T16:28:43.3117352Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89459/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89459/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","Government Departments: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government is taking to ensure the protection of personal data held by private companies operating Government-shared services.","false","Biography information for Anas Sarwar","Glasgow Central","Anas Sarwar","207435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89460","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-05","<p>Successive independent evaluations have shown that National Citizen Service has seen significant growth in participation across England and Northern Ireland, with the programme seeing its 100,000th participant this year. The programme is delivered by regional providers who are performance managed by the NCS Trust, an independent not-for-profit organisation. Regional performance is regularly monitored, along with other factors including quality of NCS delivery and the social mix of participants.</p><p>An independent evaluation of NCS will be published by Cabinet Office in 2015, after the conclusion of the 2014 NCS programmes, and will detail the costs and number of young participants during 2014.</p><p> </p>","Braintree","Mr Brooks Newmark","207119 ; 207122","2014-09-05T11:18:31.5456529Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89460/answer","Biography information for Mr Brooks Newmark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89460/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89460/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the number of people enrolled in the National Citizen Service.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","207123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89461","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-05","<p>Decisions taken regarding the Cabinet Office’s Social Action Fund grant to Society Network Foundation, made through the Social Investment Business, were made via the designated decision-making mechanism for this programme – the Minister for Civil Society, supported by the programme’s Advisory Panel.</p><p>The Big Lottery Fund is independent from government in its decision-making on specific funding and grant awards, and no Ministers or Cabinet Office officials had any involvement in any decisions taken by them regarding the grants made to the Society Network Foundation or Big Society Network.</p><p> </p>","Braintree","Mr Brooks Newmark","207293 ; 207294 ; 207323 ; 207324","2014-09-05T11:13:55.2967171Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89461/answer","Biography information for Mr Brooks Newmark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89461/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89461/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","Big Society Network","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which officials in his Department made the decision to refer the bids for grants from the Big Lottery Fund to the Big Society Network and the Society Network Foundation back to the Social Investment Business.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","207295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89462","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-05","<p>Decisions taken regarding the Cabinet Office’s Social Action Fund grant to Society Network Foundation, made through the Social Investment Business, were made via the designated decision-making mechanism for this programme – the Minister for Civil Society, supported by the programme’s Advisory Panel.</p><p>The Big Lottery Fund is independent from government in its decision-making on specific funding and grant awards, and no Ministers or Cabinet Office officials had any involvement in any decisions taken by them regarding the grants made to the Society Network Foundation or Big Society Network.</p><p> </p>","Braintree","Mr Brooks Newmark","207293 ; 207295 ; 207323 ; 207324","2014-09-05T11:13:55.2370217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89462/answer","Biography information for Mr Brooks Newmark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89462/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89462/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","Big Society Network","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which grade of officials in his Department made the decision to refer the bids for grants from the Big Lottery Fund and the Cabinet Office to the Big Society Network and the Society Network Foundation back to the Social Investment Business.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","207294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89463","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-05","<p>Decisions taken regarding the Cabinet Office’s Social Action Fund grant to Society Network Foundation, made through the Social Investment Business, were made via the designated decision-making mechanism for this programme – the Minister for Civil Society, supported by the programme’s Advisory Panel.</p><p>The Big Lottery Fund is independent from government in its decision-making on specific funding and grant awards, and no Ministers or Cabinet Office officials had any involvement in any decisions taken by them regarding the grants made to the Society Network Foundation or Big Society Network.</p><p> </p>","Braintree","Mr Brooks Newmark","207294 ; 207295 ; 207323 ; 207324","2014-09-05T11:13:55.1676865Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89463/answer","Biography information for Mr Brooks Newmark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89463/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89463/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","Big Society Network","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which Minister authorised the decision to refer the bids from the Big Lottery Fund and the Cabinet Office to the Big Society Network and the Society Network Foundation back to the Social Investment Business.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","207293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89464","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-05","<p>The Big Lottery Fund is independent of government in its decision-making on funding and grant awards.</p><p> </p>","Braintree","Mr Brooks Newmark",,"2014-09-05T11:08:57.8167611Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89464/answer","Biography information for Mr Brooks Newmark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89464/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89464/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","Big Lottery Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he willl take steps to revise the criteria for awarding grants to ensure that organisations less than two years old cannot apply for grants from the Big Lottery Fund.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","207304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89465","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-05","<p>Decisions taken regarding the Cabinet Office’s Social Action Fund grant to Society Network Foundation, made through the Social Investment Business, were made via the designated decision-making mechanism for this programme – the Minister for Civil Society, supported by the programme’s Advisory Panel.</p><p>The Big Lottery Fund is independent from government in its decision-making on specific funding and grant awards, and no Ministers or Cabinet Office officials had any involvement in any decisions taken by them regarding the grants made to the Society Network Foundation or Big Society Network.</p><p> </p>","Braintree","Mr Brooks Newmark","207293 ; 207294 ; 207295 ; 207324","2014-09-05T11:13:55.3592603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89465/answer","Biography information for Mr Brooks Newmark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89465/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89465/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","Big Society Network","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which official in his Department authorised the Cabinet Office's payment to the Society Network Foundation for the Get In project in October 2012.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","207323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89466","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-05","<p>Decisions taken regarding the Cabinet Office’s Social Action Fund grant to Society Network Foundation, made through the Social Investment Business, were made via the designated decision-making mechanism for this programme – the Minister for Civil Society, supported by the programme’s Advisory Panel.</p><p>The Big Lottery Fund is independent from government in its decision-making on specific funding and grant awards, and no Ministers or Cabinet Office officials had any involvement in any decisions taken by them regarding the grants made to the Society Network Foundation or Big Society Network.</p><p> </p>","Braintree","Mr Brooks Newmark","207293 ; 207294 ; 207295 ; 207323","2014-09-05T11:13:55.4217607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89466/answer","Biography information for Mr Brooks Newmark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89466/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89466/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","Big Society Network","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which Minister authorised the Cabinet Office's payment to the Society Network Foundation for the Get In project in October 2012.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","207324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89467","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-05","<p>The Get In project experienced difficulties in its first quarter. The Cabinet Office worked with Society Network Foundation to assess whether these difficulties could be overcome. When it was concluded that they could not, the project was stopped and Cabinet Office paid only up to that point. This is standard practice when funding small charities to undertake innovative projects.</p><p>The Civil Society Compact states that funders should attempt to support organisations overcome difficulties and should give at least three months’ notice before ending a financial relationship with a charitable organisation.</p><p>The Social Investment Business is currently following their standard procedure to investigate and take appropriate action where funds received by Social Network Foundation for the Get In project may not have been used for the purposes for which the grant was given.</p><p>Regarding grant funds spent on the Get In project, Cabinet Office would not normally seek to recover funds spent in line with a grant agreement.</p><p> </p>","Braintree","Mr Brooks Newmark","207322","2014-09-05T11:11:36.8913254Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89467/answer","Biography information for Mr Brooks Newmark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89467/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89467/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","Big Society Network","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, for what reasons his Department made a second payment to the Society Network Foundation for the Get In project in October 2012.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","207325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89468","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-05","<p>The Cabinet Office has not had any discussions with NESTA regarding funding for the Big Society Network, and did not approach NESTA or Big Lottery Fund and ask them to fund the Big Society Network.</p><p>No discussions with Big Lottery Fund concerning the Society Network Foundation or Big Society Network were held by either Cabinet Office Ministers or Officials.</p><p>Cabinet Office holds regular sponsorship meetings with Big Lottery Fund, which cover governance, accounting and efficiency issues but not funding applications or decisions.</p><p> </p>","Braintree","Mr Brooks Newmark","207320 ; 207321","2014-09-05T11:16:21.4762548Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89468/answer","Biography information for Mr Brooks Newmark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89468/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89468/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","Big Society Network","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many discussions (a) Ministers and (b) officials in his Department had with the Big Lottery fund prior to that organisation approaching the Big Society Network to apply for a grant.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","207303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89469","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-09-18","<p>The Department does not collate or hold any detailed informaton relating to individual local authorities' workforces. <br><br>The Office for National Statistics collates workforce information from local authorites as part of its quarterly public sector employment survey. These statistics are available on the Local Government Association website at http://www.local.gov.uk/local-government-intelligence/-/journal_content/56/10180/2991184/ARTICLE.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-09-18T16:30:17.6536471Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89469/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89469/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89469/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-08-29","Employment: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many (a) full-time, (b) part-time, (c) self-employed, (d) casual, (e) fixed-term or contract, (f) apprenticeship and (g) commission-only workers there are in each local authority in Lancashire.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham Jones","207432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89470","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-03","<p>The Business Appointment Rules apply to those people employed in civil service, the diplomatic service and members of the armed services, whether the employment is paid or unpaid.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-09-03T16:27:28.2388233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89470/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89470/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89470/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","Public Sector: Business Interests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Business Appointment Rules for public servants relate to (a) appointments in (i) NGOs, (ii) charities and (iii) other non-commercial organisations and (b) unpaid positions.","false","Biography information for Charlie Elphicke","Dover","Charlie Elphicke","207503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89471","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-03","<p>Overall government spend with SMEs has increased from £3 billion in 2009/10 to £4.5 billion in 2012/13, putting us on track to deliver our aspiration of awarding 25% of central government business to small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) by 2015. Figures for 2013-14 will be published in the autumn.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-09-03T14:16:52.9703555Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89471/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89471/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89471/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","Government Departments: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of central Government procurement spend was with small and medium-sized enterprises on 21 August 2014.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","207479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89472","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-05","<p>The Cabinet Office has transposed two EU directives into UK law since 2010 and six directly applicable regulations have come into effect in the Cabinet Office’s area of responsibility in the same period.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-09-05T11:00:41.0043336Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89472/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89472/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89472/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-08-29","EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many new EU directives and regulations have been transposed into UK law by his Department since May 2010.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","Mr John Redwood","207253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89473","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-10","<p>To date the Government has invested £105 million in support of the Armed Forces Covenant much of which is benifiting or will benefit veterans across the UK. Veterans in the South West have benefited from a range of projects based either in the South West or operating UK wide worth in excess of £11.5 million. We expect further projects in the South West to benefit in the near future and in the long term when the new £10 million Armed Forces Covenant Fund is introduced in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Projects in the South West are funded via the Community Covenant Grant Scheme and a £35 million LIBOR Fund.</p><p> </p><p>A list of successful projects to date can be found attached.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-09-10T13:09:58.4730448Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89473/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89473/answer","Part of answer to 207533 - Community Covenant Grant Scheme.doc","Part of answer to 207533 - Community Covenant Grant Scheme.doc","Part of answer to 207533","Part of answer to 207533","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89473/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89473/answer/previousversion/18514","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-08-29","Armed Forces Covenant: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which organisations working with veterans in the South West have received money under the Armed Forces Covenant Fund to date.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","207533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89474","HM Treasury","false","2014-09-05","<p>Details of all current EU legislation are on the Euro – Lex website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://eur-lex.europa.eu/browse/directories/legislation.html" target="_blank">http://eur-lex.europa.eu/browse/directories/legislation.html</a></p><p>We do not hold a central record of the EU directives the Treasury has transposed into UK law since 2010 nor a record of all EU regulations that came into effect during that period.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-09-05T13:08:42.0081459Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89474/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89474/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89474/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-08-29","EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many new EU directives and regulations have been transposed into UK law by his Department since May 2010.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","Mr John Redwood","207266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89475","HM Treasury","false","2014-09-04","<p>This Government is committed to strong and sustainable growth that is balanced across the economy. Manufacturing, including textile manufacturing, is a vital part of this. Textile manufacturing has received direct support from the Government; including awarding £12.8m of grant funding to the Textiles Growth Programme through the Regional Growth Fund, which is being used to support capital investment, training, and research and development in the textile industry.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Textile manufacturing, and indeed all manufacturing, in the UK is also being supported by various measures announced in the most recent Budget. This includes increasing the Annual Investment Allowance to £500,000 until 31 December 2015, raising the rate of the R&amp;D tax credit payable to loss making SMEs to 14.5%, and the package of measures to reduce manufacturers’ energy bills and improve UK competitiveness.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2014-09-04T14:02:30.3619673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89475/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89475/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89475/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-08-29","Textiles: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what fiscal steps his Department is taking to boost textile manufacturing in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr David Ward","Bradford East","Mr David Ward","207526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89476","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-09-03","<p> </p><p>We have introduced a £1 billion business rate support package for 2014-15 including:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><ul><li>a 2 per cent cap in the Retail Price Index increase;</li><li>a discount of £1,000 for around 300,000 shops, pubs and restaurants with</li><li>rateable values below £50,000,</li><li>doubling small business rate relief extended for another year benefitting over half a million businesses;</li><li>a 50 per cent discount for new occupants of long-term vacant shops, and</li><li>allowing ratepayers to pay bills over 12 instalments.</li></ul></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This package will benefit all businesses but particularly those with a lower rateable</p><p> </p><p>value. Local authority forecasts of business rates are not available split by rateable</p><p> </p><p>value threshold or business sector.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As at 31 March 2013, 89% of hereditaments had a rateable value of £50,000 or</p><p> </p><p>lower. As at 31 March 2013, large properties (those with a rateable value equal to</p><p> </p><p>or greater than £50,000) account for 72% of rateable value. These data are taken</p><p> </p><p>from the Valuation Office Agency’s disclosure log, available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.voa.gov.uk/corporate/About/Policy/disclosureLogResponses2013.html" target="_blank">http://www.voa.gov.uk/corporate/About/Policy/disclosureLogResponses2013.html</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins","207516 ; 207518 ; 207519","2014-09-03T14:26:18.2931572Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89476/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89476/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89476/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-08