"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89480","HM Treasury","false","2014-09-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs' Debt Management and Banking directorate has looked at existing capacity across its locations, specific functional requirements and IT infrastructure and used the availability of people and management to determine locations.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-09-03T15:32:25.7234908Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89480/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89480/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89480/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-08-29","Revenue and Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what criteria were used to determine the location of new posts within the HM Revenue and Customs Debt Management Directorate.","false","Biography information for Ann McKechin","Glasgow North","Ann McKechin","207480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89481","HM Treasury","false","2014-09-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) Debt Management &amp; Banking Directorate is recruiting staff in locations across the country where it has specific functional requirements and the IT infrastructure to support the work.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It has posts immediately available in East Kilbride and Cumbernauld. These jobs have been made available to all staff on fixed term appointments nationwide, including those currently working in Glasgow. Some of these members of staff have applied for jobs in East Kilbride and Cumbernauld. HMRC is continuing to look at options for the remaining staff within the Personal Tax line of business who want to continue their employment with HMRC.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-09-03T15:34:41.0585786Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89481/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89481/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89481/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-08-29","Revenue and Customs: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will confirm why HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) staff currently employed in the Personal Tax Operations Directorate office in Glasgow and who wish to be transferred to HMRC Debt Management Directorate are not allowed to continue to work in HMRC Glasgow offices.","false","Biography information for Ann McKechin","Glasgow North","Ann McKechin","207481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89482","HM Treasury","false","2014-09-03","<p>Wherever possible, HM Revenue &amp; Customs aims to fill vacancies in the locations where its existing functions are already based. This is to ensure that suitable accommodation and IT is available and appropriate management to support new employees is in place on site.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-09-03T15:30:09.9409451Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89482/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89482/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89482/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-08-29","Revenue and Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the work of the HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) Debt Management Directorate can be carried out at any (a) HMRC office and (b) HMRC office currently used for the work of the Personal Tax Operations Directorate.","false","Biography information for Ann McKechin","Glasgow North","Ann McKechin","207482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89483","HM Treasury","false","2014-09-04","<p>Reports by the British Geological Survey’s clearly demonstrate the potential for shale gas in the UK. Shale gas has the potential to increase our energy security, generate growth and support thousands of jobs, and the government is doing everything it can to support the safe and sustainable development of shale gas. This is why we introduced the onshore allowance, to incentivise investment in onshore oil and gas projects and kick-start exploration. Last year, the industry also announced that local communities would receive £100,000 when a test well is fracked – and a further 1 per cent of revenues if shale gas is discovered.</p><p> </p><p>More work is needed to determine the extent of the gas that can be technically and commercially recovered. While there is clearly potential for shale gas to provide substantial revenue to the Exchequer in the future, no forecasts have been produced on the scale or timing of the revenue.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2014-09-04T13:55:43.2437815Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89483/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89483/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89483/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-08-29","Fracking: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of potential tax revenue to the Exchequer from shale gas and oil products in each region and constituent part of the UK.","false","Biography information for Eric Ollerenshaw","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Eric Ollerenshaw","207431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89484","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-09-03","<p> </p><p>We have introduced a £1 billion business rate support package for 2014-15 including:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><ul><li>a 2 per cent cap in the Retail Price Index increase;</li><li>a discount of £1,000 for around 300,000 shops, pubs and restaurants with</li><li>rateable values below £50,000,</li><li>doubling small business rate relief extended for another year benefitting over half a million businesses;</li><li>a 50 per cent discount for new occupants of long-term vacant shops, and</li><li>allowing ratepayers to pay bills over 12 instalments.</li></ul></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This package will benefit all businesses but particularly those with a lower rateable</p><p> </p><p>value. Local authority forecasts of business rates are not available split by rateable</p><p> </p><p>value threshold or business sector.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As at 31 March 2013, 89% of hereditaments had a rateable value of £50,000 or</p><p> </p><p>lower. As at 31 March 2013, large properties (those with a rateable value equal to</p><p> </p><p>or greater than £50,000) account for 72% of rateable value. These data are taken</p><p> </p><p>from the Valuation Office Agency’s disclosure log, available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.voa.gov.uk/corporate/About/Policy/disclosureLogResponses2013.html" target="_blank">http://www.voa.gov.uk/corporate/About/Policy/disclosureLogResponses2013.html</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins","207517 ; 207518 ; 207519","2014-09-03T14:26:18.228155Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89484/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89484/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89484/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-08-29","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of premises on the rating list have a rateable value of less than £50,000.","false","Biography information for Simon Danczuk","Rochdale","Simon Danczuk","207516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89485","HM Treasury","false","2014-09-09","<p>The estimated annual fiscal saving as a result of the high income child benefit charge has been published by HM Treasury and the Office for Budget Responsibility at fiscal events.</p><p> </p><p>The administrative costs of the high income child benefit charge were included in the National Audit Office 20/12-13 HMRC Standard Report:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/10174-001_HMRC_Standard-report.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/10174-001_HMRC_Standard-report.pdf</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-09-09T14:59:34.2798451Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89485/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89485/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89485/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-08-29","Child Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the saving to the public purse will be from the removal of child benefit for households where one parent earns £50,000; and what estimate he has made of the increase in administration costs arising from such a policy.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","207461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89486","HM Treasury","false","2014-09-09","<p> </p><p>I have been asked to reply on behalf of the Minister of State for Culture and the Digital Economy.</p><p>The total value of items accepted under the Acceptance-in-Lieu Scheme for the last five years is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>2009 £19.8m</p><p>2010 £15.7m</p><p>2011 £8.3m</p><p>2012 £31.3m</p><p>2013 £49.4m*</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>*includes the first item accepted under the Cultural Gifts Scheme which operates from the same budget as the Acceptance-in-Lieu Scheme.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-09-09T09:57:33.8691504Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89486/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89486/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89486/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-08-29","Objects in Lieu of Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the total value of works of art accepted in lieu of inheritance tax was in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","207429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89487","HM Treasury","false","2014-09-03","<p>On 7<sup>th</sup> August 2014, the European Commission released a short summary of their decision on the Aggregates Levy Credit scheme. The full decision will be released by the commission in the coming weeks once commercially sensitive information has been redacted.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2014-09-03T13:50:07.7045627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89487/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89487/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-08-29","Aggregates Levy: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he expects the European Commission to make a decision on the Aggregate Credit Levy scheme.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","207469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89488","HM Treasury","false","2014-09-04","<p>Officials have been in regular discussions with the European Commission in regards to their decision on the Aggregates Credit Levy Scheme. Further to this on 7<sup>th</sup> August 2014, the European Commission released a short summary of their decision on the investigation in to the compatibility of the scheme with State Aid guidelines. Their decision finds that the aid met the Environmental Aid Guidelines. The full, detailed, decision will be published once commercially sensitive information has been redacted.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2014-09-04T14:00:15.6994935Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89488/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89488/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-08-29","Aggregates Levy: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions his Department has held with European Commission officials on the Aggregate Credit Levy scheme.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","207470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89489","HM Treasury","false","2014-09-05","<p>The Government has fundamentally reformed regulation of the consumer credit market. Responsibility for consumer credit regulation transferred from the Office of Fair Trading (OFT) to the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) on 1 April 2014.</p><p> </p><p>In the FCA’s consultation paper on the cap on the cost of payday loans, the FCA assesses that its proposals will lead to a risk of contraction in both the online and high-street markets. FCA modelling suggests that its cap proposals would mean at least one high street firm would continue to offer payday loans and at least the three largest online firms continuing in the market, although the FCA expects that more firms will be able to adapt their businesses to operate under the price cap and remain in the market.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-09-05T13:16:20.2909509Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89489/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89489/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-08-29","Credit: Interest Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of (a) the number of payday firms that will be in operation and (b) the projected consumer demand for payday loans in (i) 2015, (ii) 2016 and (iii) 2017.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","207342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89490","HM Treasury","false","2014-09-08","<p>The Government has made clear to lenders that credit data sharing is key to proper affordability assessments and promoting a competitive market, and more progress on recording and using payday lending data in real time is vital to addressing problems around multiple loans.</p><p> </p><p>Having access to comprehensive real-time data about their customers’ outstanding commitments may help avoid consumers taking out a loan which they cannot afford to repay.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA has already made clear to payday lenders and credit reference agencies (CRAs) in its policy statement, published in February, that they must identify and remove any data sharing blockages involving payday lenders as a matter of urgency.</p><p> </p><p>In its consultation on the cap on the cost of payday loans, published in July, the FCA stated it expects to see more than 90% of current market participants - by market share and volume of loans - participating in real-time market-wide data sharing by November 2014, and more than 90% of loans being reported in real time. In order to improve the coverage of real-time databases, firms will also need to share data with more than one CRA.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA stated that it will request information from firms and CRAs in order to get an accurate picture of whether the standards it has proposed have been met by November. If the FCA does not see sufficient progress by November or CRA coverage does not improve, it will consult on the introduction of data sharing requirements. It has also placed a requirement on firms to provide product sales data on high-cost short-term credit agreements every three months once they are authorised.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Credit reference agencies must ensure that that their use of personal data is compliant with the Data Protection Act 1998 (DPA). The Information Commissioner’s Office is an independent UK supervisory authority that oversees and enforces compliance with the DPA.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","207339 ; 207341 ; 207344 ; 207380","2014-09-08T15:45:34.2403155Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89490/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89490/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-08-29","Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will take steps to prohibit credit reference agencies from selling payday customer details to marketing agencies and lead generators.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","207340"
